  <header class="row-fluid page-header">
    <h1 class="first"><span class="t">T</span><small><span class="firstLine">he Book of Jack was supposed to be</span><span class="small"> an entertaining exploration of the name &#147;Jack&#148;, its origins and usage, the letter &#147;j&#148; and even the sound &#147;dzh&#148;. Once I started however, this project took on a life of its own and eventually, after many iterations, morphed into this web site. <sup id="fnref:1.1" class="footnote"><a href="/about#fn:1.1">1</a></sup></span></small>
    </h1>
  </header>

  <section class="row-fluid">
    <div class="span4 columns">
      <p>This photograph is of a Geneva Bible that was printed in 1581. <sup id="fnref:1.2" class="footnote"><a href="/about#fn:1.2">2</a></sup></p>
      
      <p>A little blasphemous maybe, but it&#039;s as good a place to start as any.... You see, the letter &#147;j&#148; is absent from this bible, it hadn&#039;t even been invented yet&#033; <sup id="fnref:1.3" class="footnote"><a href="/about#fn:1.3">3</a></sup></p>
      
      <p>I&#039;m wondering how they spelled Jesus, Jacob and Jerusalem&#063; And, if they didn&#039;t use the letter &#147;J&#148;, which has a &#147;dzh&#148; sound, how <em>did</em> they pronounce the names Jesus, Jacob and Jerusalem&#063;</p>
    </div>

